==Description==
{{Blurimage|file=28eb57b879cee2611effff7d8b3645e5.webp|hovertext=It's all hazy...|caption=An artist's rendition of blurring, pieced together from different descriptions of memories.}}

'''Blurring''' is a poorly-understood anomalous mental hazard that affects wanderers in extremely dark places, chiefly [[The Void|<span style="color:#CFCFCF;">the Void</span>]]. Blurring is frequently described as 'blinking and being somewhere else'. The most common interpretation of this statement is one being instantaneously transported to a new place and time, without recalling how one arrived. Commonly associated with a lacking of or 'blurry' memory, remembrance of the process of blurring is shoddy at best, and overwhelmingly rare. This phenomenon almost entirely occurs to those currently in [[The Void|<span style="color:#CFCFCF;">the Void</span>]], which creates large gaps in one's memory due to the sensory deprivation. It is unknown if the recollections are barely a fraction or the whole of the process behind blurring. Although this phenomenon has been occurred elsewhere, it has never been recorded in the company of others.

Memories of blurring are notably distorted and blurry (hence the name), and recalling them in sufficient detail is almost impossible. Those affected describe it as every memory stopping the rest from exiting as it itself yearns for freedom, trapping themselves in the back of the mind, blurry and unable to be recalled. The few that can be adequately recalled usually have strange, nonsensical or inconsistent details, and commonly involve a motif of shattering. Those who attempt to recall all memories of blurring are suddenly hit with a mental wave of distress, often accompanied by the development of mental disorders. Keeping a journal for documentation has proven fruitless, as there is a sudden gap in writing during the phenomenon, with any sensical writing being replaced with random letters and scribbles, with some portions of the page being [[Level REDACTED|<span style="color:#CFCFCF;">redacted</span>]].

Individuals actively experiencing blurring tend to forget key things such as where they were, who the are, and when they are. Afflicted persons exhibit an increased pain tolerance and a degree of emotional detachment, which are typically traced to their 'detachment' from the world as a whole during blurring. Blurring has no set length, with the longest ever blurring having lasted two months and three days, although people stuck in [[The Void|<span style="color:#CFCFCF;">the Void</span>]] have almost certainly experienced it for longer. Immediate aftereffects include panic attacks and severe paranoia, and scarcely bleeding from the eyes and mouth.

Blurring often results in one finding themselves in a place entirely unrelated from their original location. This can include entering [[Level 87|dead-end levels]] or levels that require multiple no-clips to arrive at. While blurring may lead to dangerous levels, it never leaves one in actively dangerous situations. The levels one most commonly ends up in are typically levels with a strong connection to the void, such as [[Level 483|<span style="color:#CFCFCF;">Level 483</span>]]. The following is a list of blurring durations and where they inevitably led.

